\subsection{Conjecture 1: Bounds from Word Order}






























 As we discussed briefly above, for words of a fixed, even length,
we conjecture that ${\operatorname{tr}} (O_\pm^N)$ is the smallest and ${\operatorname{tr}} [ (O_+ O_-)^{N/2} ]$ is the largest
among the traces.  
In the notation of the previous section, we expect that the trace of an arbitrary word
$O_+^{n_1} O_-^{n_2} \cdots$ of length $N$ is bounded above and below by
\begin{eqnarray}
{\operatorname{tr}} (O_+^N) = {\operatorname{tr}}[ (O_+ O_-)^{N/2}] X^{N/4} \leq  {\operatorname{tr}}(O_+^{n_1} O_-^{n_2} \cdots) \leq {\operatorname{tr}}[ (O_+ O_-)^{N/2}]   \ .
\end{eqnarray}

We can refine this conjecture on word order further.  Define $s = |n_+ - n_-|$ to be the difference between the number of times $n_+$ that $O_+$ appears in a word and the times $n_-$ that $O_-$ appears in a word.  For two words $W_1$ and $W_2$, we conjecture that if $s(W_1) > s(W_2)$, then ${\operatorname{tr}}(W_1) < {\operatorname{tr}} (W_2)$.  Indeed, we have checked this conjecture in the two interval case for small $N$, using the explicit representation of these traces in terms of Riemann-Siegel theta functions.  See figure \ref{fig:wordorder}.  

Given this refined conjecture on word order, we can obtain upper and lower bounds on the negativity.  For an upper bound, we first consider all the terms in the binomial expansion of ${\operatorname{tr}}[(\rho_A^{T_2})^{N/2}]$ that appear with a positive sign such that $s \neq 0$.  We replace every word with charge $s$ with a word of charge $s-4$ and hence larger trace.  (Note there will be no traces of words of charge $s-2$ with nonzero coefficient.)  Because the number of words grows as the charge decreases, we will still have a net negative contribution from words of charge $s-4$.  We then replace all the traces of words with negative coefficient by the yet smaller trace ${\operatorname{tr}}(O_+)^N$.  For the words of charge $s=0$, we simply replace all of them by the larger ${\operatorname{tr}}[(O_+ O_-)^{N/2}]$.  At the end of this procedure, we find the following upper bound
\begin{eqnarray}
{\operatorname{tr}}[ (\rho_A^{T_2})^{N/2}] \leq \left[1 - \frac{1}{2^{N/2}} {N \choose \frac{N}{2} } \right] {\operatorname{tr}}(O_+^N) + \frac{1}{2^{N/2}}  {N \choose \frac{N}{2} } {\operatorname{tr}}[(O_+ O_-)^{N/2}] \ .
\end{eqnarray} 
In the large $N$ limit, the right hand side of this expression approaches
\begin{eqnarray}
\sqrt{\frac{2^{N+1}}{\pi N}} \left( {\operatorname{tr}} [(O_+ O_-)^{N/2}] - {\operatorname{tr}}(O_+^N) \right) \ ,
\end{eqnarray}
which appears to be a somewhat more stringent condition than our rigorous upper bound (\ref{eq:tib}). 

We can obtain a lower bound in a similar fashion, reversing the procedure.  We consider all the terms in the binomial expansion of 
${\operatorname{tr}}[(\rho_A^{T_2})^{N/2}]$ that appear with negative coefficient.  We replace every word with charge $s$ by a word of charge $s-4$.  All the traces will then have positive coefficient.  Next, except for ${\operatorname{tr}} [(O_+ O_-)^{N/2}]$ itself,  we replace all the traces of words with the smaller ${\operatorname{tr}}(O_+)^N$.  In this case, we find the lower bound
\begin{eqnarray}
\left(1 - \frac{1}{2^{N/2 - 1}} \right) {\operatorname{tr}} (O_+^N) + \frac{1}{2^{N/2 - 1}} {\operatorname{tr}}[(O_+ O_-)^{N/2}] \leq {\operatorname{tr}}[ (\rho_A^{T_2})^{N/2}]  \ .
\end{eqnarray}
In comparison with the conjecture we discuss next, this lower bound is not particularly stringent in the large $N$ limit.  

We can establish these bounds rigorously only for small $N$.  Note that for $N=2$, the upper and lower bound reduce to the known equality (\ref{negtwo}).  For $N=4$ and $N=6$, we obtain the constraints

